%md

# World Development Indicators

Author: Paul Bustios

## Table of contents

1. Introduction
2. Requirements
3. Objective
5. Getting and preparing the data
6. Exploratory analysis

## 1. Introduction

The [World Development Indicators][1] are a collection of data about the global development, compiled from many sources and made available by the [World Bank][2]. In addition to this dataset, there are many [others][3] publicly available by the World Bank's Open Data initiative. In order to vizualize some of these development indicators, in this notebook we want to show them in an easy way through maps and interactive graphics using [R][4] and some well known packages to plot data.


## 2. Requirements

To be able to execute the code in this notebook, it is necessary to have installed R and the next packages:

- rworldmap
- ggplot2
- maps
- reshape2
- googleVis

If you do not have these packages, you can execute the next command in your R session to install them:

    install.packages(c("rworldmap", "ggplot2", "maps", "reshape2", "googleVis"), repos = "http://cran.r-project.org")

## 3. Objective

The objective of this notebook is to show some indicators of the World Development Indicators dataset in an easy way through maps and interactive graphics using [R][4] as the main programming language and some well known packages to plot geographical data. In order to do that, we will have to do some [data wrangling][5].

## 4. Getting and preparing the data

As we said, we will use the World Development Indicators as data source in this notebook, so the first step will be to download these dataset with the next code:

[1]: http://data.worldbank.org/data-catalog/world-development-indicators
[2]: http://www.worldbank.org/
[3]: http://datacatalog.worldbank.org/
[4]: https://www.r-project.org/
[5]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_wrangling

%md

## 5. Exploratory analysis

Read the data using the **read.csv** function and print the summary of the data to ensure that it was loaded. The World Development Indicators dataset is composed of 248 indicators from 1960 to 2015.

result.msg:
5. Exploratory analysis

Read the data using the read.csv function and print the summary of the data to ensure that it was loaded. The World Development Indicators dataset is composed of 248 indicators from 1960 to 2015.

paragraphs.title: Reading the data
paragraphs.text:
%r

data <- read.csv("/tmp/WDI_Data.csv", check.names = FALSE)
summary(data)

%md
Now, we are going to select the indicators of interest and remove the object **data** to release memory.

result.msg: Now, we are going to select the indicators of interest and remove the object data to release memory.

paragraphs.text:
%r

fertIndName <- "Fertility rate, total (births per woman)"
lifeIndName <- "Life expectancy at birth, total (years)"
popuIndName <- "Population, total"

fertInd <- data[data$"Indicator Name" == fertIndName, c(1, 2, 5:60)]
lifeInd <- data[data$"Indicator Name" == lifeIndName, c(2, 5:60)]
popuInd <- data[data$"Indicator Name" == popuIndName, c(2, 5:60)]

rm(data)
gcinfo(TRUE)
gc()

%md

We are going to visualize the life expectancy in 2014 in the world. For that, the package **rworldmap** will be used. First, we need to join the indicator with the list of countries that this package has internally using the field **Country Code** which contains the countries' [ISO codes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1_alpha-3).

result.msg: We are going to visualize the life expectancy in 2014 in the world. For that, the package rworldmap will be used. First, we need to join the indicator with the list of countries that this package has internally using the field Country Code which contains the countries' ISO codes.

paragraphs.text:
%r

library(rworldmap)

sPDF <- joinCountryData2Map(lifeInd,
                            joinCode="ISO3", # To use 3-letter ISO code
                            nameJoinColumn="Country Code",
                            verbose=TRUE)

%r

common <- fertInd$"Country Name" %in% names(correction)

paragraphs.text:
%md

Now, with the correct country names, we are going to plot the fertility rate in 2014.

result.msg: Now, with the correct country names, we are going to plot the fertility rate in 2014.

paragraphs.text:
%r

library(ggplot2)
library(maps)

colnames(fertInd)[57] <- "X2014"

mapWorld <- merge(x=map_data(map="world"),
                  y=fertInd,
                  by.x="region",
                  by.y="Country Name",
                  all.x=TRUE)

mapWorld <- mapWorld[order(mapWorld$order),]

p <- ggplot(mapWorld) +
     geom_map(map=mapWorld, aes(map_id=region, x=long, y=lat, fill=X2014)) + 
     coord_equal() +
     ggtitle("Fertility rate in 2014") + 
     theme(legend.title=element_blank(),
           axis.text.x=element_blank(),
           axis.text.y=element_blank(),
           axis.ticks=element_blank(),
           axis.title.x=element_blank(),
           axis.title.y=element_blank(),
           legend.position="bottom")

%md

We are going to select some countries to plot the evolution of the fertility and the life expectancy across the time.

result.msg: We are going to select some countries to plot the evolution of the fertility and the life expectancy across the time.

paragraphs.text:
%r

library("reshape2")

# Restore the name of the column 57 to 2014 
colnames(fertInd)[57] <- "2014"

fertInd$"Country Name" <- as.factor(fertInd$"Country Name")

fertIndReshaped <- melt(fertInd,
                        id.vars = c("Country Name", "Country Code"),
                        variable.name = "Year",
                        value.name = "Fertility")
lifeIndReshaped <- melt(lifeInd,
                        id.vars = "Country Code",
                        variable.name = "Year",
                        value.name = "Life")
popuIndReshaped <- melt(popuInd,
                        id.vars = "Country Code",
                        variable.name = "Year",
                        value.name = "Population")

allInd <- merge(merge(fertIndReshaped,
                      lifeIndReshaped,
                      by.x = c("Country Code", "Year"),
                      by.y = c("Country Code", "Year")),
                popuIndReshaped,
                by.x = c("Country Code", "Year"),
                by.y = c("Country Code", "Year"))

# Casting "Year" type from Factor to Numeric
allInd$Year <- as.numeric(levels(allInd$Year))[allInd$Year]

# Removing NA values
allInd <- allInd[!is.na(allInd$Fertility) & 
                 !is.na(allInd$Life) &
                 !is.na(allInd$Population), ]

countries <- c("ARG", "BRA", "KHM", "CHN", "COL", "DEU", "GBR", "IND", "JPN", 
               "KEN", "KOR", "NGA", "PER", "RWA", "SAU", "SDN", "USA", "ZAF")
selectedCountries <- allInd[allInd$"Country Code" %in% countries, ]

summary(selectedCountries)
